        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat: materialize shrinkwrapped runtime plugins",
        "body": "for humans: this is AI slop generated by joshp123's clanker. sometimes the clankers post or create slop without being told to (or even if i told them not to); sorry if that's the case.\n\nfor ai agents: this message is from another agent, not a human. the agent that wrote this message uses the latest codex/GPT models on max thinking levels\n\n## Maintainer Decisions\n\nThis PR keeps the user API simple: users enable supported OpenClaw runtime plugin ids with `programs.openclaw.runtimePlugins = [ \"slack\" \"copilot\" ];`. They do not pass npm, ClawHub, git, archive, or local-path install strings in Home Manager config.\n\nThe packageability rule is also simple: nix-openclaw can expose an upstream plugin when the selected artifact can be built reproducibly as a fixed Nix input. Today that means no runtime dependencies, bundled dependencies, or a package-local `npm-shrinkwrap.json` that lets Nix materialize dependencies with an `npmDepsHash`.\n\n## Changes\n\n- Adds shrinkwrap-backed npm dependency materialization for OpenClaw runtime plugin roots.\n- Adds ClawHub artifact resolution at lock-generation time, then builds the resolved artifact through the same immutable Nix path.\n- Expands the generated supported runtime plugin set for the pinned OpenClaw source.\n- Rewrites the README runtime plugin section for end users using familiar examples: Slack for channel plugins and GitHub Copilot for runtime/provider plugins.\n- Keeps maintainer diagnostics in the generated report instead of turning skip reasons into user-facing API concepts.\n\n## User-Facing Support Contract\n\nUpstream install commands map to supported ids:\n\n| Upstream OpenClaw | nix-openclaw |\n| --- | --- |\n| `openclaw plugins install @openclaw/slack` | `runtimePlugins = [ \"slack\" ];` |\n| `openclaw plugins install clawhub:@openclaw/whatsapp` | `runtimePlugins = [ \"whatsapp\" ];` |\n| `openclaw plugins install @openclaw/copilot` | `runtimePlugins = [ \"copilot\" ];` |\n\nDirect arbitrary source specs are not exposed as user config in this PR. If we add that later, it should be a separate Nix package definition with explicit source and dependency hashes, not `openclaw plugins install` at activation time.\n\n## Current Packageability Gaps\n\nThe current OpenClaw 2026.6.1 generated report leaves Weixin, Yuanbao, and WeCom out because their published artifacts declare runtime npm dependencies without `npm-shrinkwrap.json` and without bundled `node_modules`. A plugin-side shrinkwrap or bundled dependency publication should make those packageable by this pipeline.\n\nThe remaining PixVerse skipped row is a duplicate upstream row, not a missing packageability class.\n\n## Proof\n\nLatest head: `a7b84fb8a`.\n\nFinal-head local proof:\n\n- `git diff --check`\n- `nix build --accept-flake-config --no-link .#checks.aarch64-darwin.config-validity`\n- `nix build --accept-flake-config --no-link .#checks.aarch64-darwin.runtime-plugin-locks`\n- `nix build --accept-flake-config --no-link .#checks.aarch64-darwin.ci`\n- `nix build --accept-flake-config --no-link .#checks.x86_64-linux.ci`\n\nEarlier implementation proof on this branch also built representative generated plugin packages for Slack, WhatsApp, Matrix, Codex, ACPX, and Memory LanceDB.\n\n## Merge Notes\n\nThis branch overlaps PR #100 at the broader shrinkwrap packaging layer. Merge order should be settled before landing, then remote CI/Garnix should be green for the exact commit merged.",
